the claims for which Google &lt;a href="http://www.groklaw.net/article.php?story=20110817200754569"&gt;requested&lt;/a&gt; reexamination.

The USPTO has already taken the next step of issuing a &lt;a href="http://www.groklaw.net/pdf3/LodsysReexam-078-004.pdf"&gt;Non-Final Action&lt;/a&gt; in which it affirmed seven of the challenged claims (7, 12-15, 18 and 70) but rejected all of the remaining 28 challenged claims. The rejected claims include two of the four independent claims of the patent (Independent claims 1 and 69 were challenged and rejected; independent claims 54 and 60 were not challenged.</summary><author gr:unknown-author="true"><name>(author unknown)</name></author><gr:likingUser>12991290327438162578</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11194020160568170514</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>07200070462272174885</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17609076054042857769</gr:likingUser><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://www.groklaw.net/backend/GrokLaw.rdf"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://www.groklaw.net/backend/GrokLaw.rdf</id><title type="html">Groklaw</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.groklaw.net" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1317322240463"><id gr:original-id="20110929014241932">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/dc3d87542c305c50</id><title type="html">Psystar Loses its Appeal; Licensees Have No First-Sale Rights; Costs Awarded to Apple  ~ pj</title><published>2011-09-29T18:32:00Z</published><updated>2011-09-29T18:32:00Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.groklaw.net/article.php?story=20110929014241932" type="text/html"/><summary xml:base="http://www.groklaw.net/" type="html">The &lt;a href="http://www.groklaw.net/pdf3/10-15113-7908340.pdf"&gt;ruling&lt;/a&gt; [PDF] is in on Psystar's &lt;a href="http://www.groklaw.net/staticpages/index.php?page=Psystar#psap"&gt;appeal&lt;/a&gt; of  aspects of its loss in 
&lt;a href="http://www.groklaw.net/staticpages/index.php?page=Psystar"&gt;Apple v. Psystar&lt;/a&gt;, and as expected, the appeals court has affirmed Judge William H. Alsup's &lt;a href="http://www.groklaw.net/article.php?story=20091114101637997"&gt;decision&lt;/a&gt; in that case on all the issues that truly matter.
Yes, it's the same judge who is presiding over &lt;i&gt; Oracle v. Google&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;p&gt;
Psystar didn't appeal its loss on Apple's infringement claims.  What it appealed was the judge ruling against Psystar on its counterclaim that  requiring MacOSX to be run only on Apple hardware was supposedly copyright misuse.  It also appealed the judge's &lt;a href="http://groklaw.net/article.php?story=20091215225827172"&gt;permanent injunction&lt;/a&gt; enjoining not only all current infringement but future infringement as well, meaning Rebel EFI, if you recall the Florida case Psystar &lt;a href="http://groklaw.net/article.php?story=2009082822245880"&gt;filed&lt;/a&gt; about that. And it appealed the sealing of documents in the case related to the Apple summary judgment motions. Psystar lost on the first two substantive points but won, sort of,  on the sealing issue, as I'll explain.&lt;p&gt; But what matters to most of you is what did the court say about  the first sale doctrine? In a phrase, that  the first sale doctrine does not apply
to a licensee.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</summary><author gr:unknown-author="true"><name>(author unknown)</name></author><gr:likingUser>11194020160568170514</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17609076054042857769</gr:likingUser><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://www.groklaw.net/backend/GrokLaw.rdf"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://www.groklaw.net/backend/GrokLaw.rdf</id><title type="html">Groklaw</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.groklaw.net" type="text/html"/></source></entry></feed>